    <title>Knot tiles</title>
    <content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEijlLOcmoTZCmb35e1glo4gVcCC1JsAD0YK-kjZZDpXxADAd6tmqiGZzIm4SiTy5uQptPZRhllD9BnURNq9q7MwdWBHKozO6XKGa7LhBK1eKuKF4VcX6VK5hDA-rk1345Q9sSFym8Ie_pc/s1600-h/3-12banner.jpg"&gt;&lt;img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5221431275334349266" style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center;" alt="" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEijlLOcmoTZCmb35e1glo4gVcCC1JsAD0YK-kjZZDpXxADAd6tmqiGZzIm4SiTy5uQptPZRhllD9BnURNq9q7MwdWBHKozO6XKGa7LhBK1eKuKF4VcX6VK5hDA-rk1345Q9sSFym8Ie_pc/s320/3-12banner.jpg" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Knot patterns (which might not actually represent knots, but just braids or plaits), like the one shown here, are common in Celtic design.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;One way to create knot patterns is to use a set of tiles that are put together following a few basic rules. This is not, as far as I know, a standard way to create these patterns - the  book by &lt;a href="http://www.amazon.com/Celtic-Design-Knotwork-Secret-Scribes/dp/0500276307"&gt;Aidan Meehan&lt;/a&gt;, provides a technique for drawing the patterns by hand, rather than laying them out as tiles.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A wide range of knot patterns, including the one shown above, can be created using the set of six tiles shown below. These were constructed using &lt;a href="http://www.dynamicgeometry.com/"&gt;Geometer's Sketchpad&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhHVuDgy2i68kf3W9seGAzNs3OlDqxXllcdE_7BxxqdSepefmTDJWo0YtJEx7DVJVRWWpQltihCnyLMUyJLnFgvBQY3UU5JYGhKhyphenhyphenUjB1v2l5dzin7EIyjnaJobZlAaubpFOQczXXHUHv4/s1600-h/knots+A.jpg"&gt;&lt;img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5221431868661867010" style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center;" alt="" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhHVuDgy2i68kf3W9seGAzNs3OlDqxXllcdE_7BxxqdSepefmTDJWo0YtJEx7DVJVRWWpQltihCnyLMUyJLnFgvBQY3UU5JYGhKhyphenhyphenUjB1v2l5dzin7EIyjnaJobZlAaubpFOQczXXHUHv4/s320/knots+A.jpg" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;The rules for putting these together are reasonably clear, but can be formalized. You can even come up with a notation for the tiles and formal rules for assembling them  into knot patterns.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When laying down the tiles, you have the option of rotating them - some of the tiles don't alter with rotation, some of them can be placed in two ways, some in four.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A nice property of this set is that you can't paint yourself into a corner when using it - you can always find a tile that will compose with the pattern that you have started. This property means that this set of tiles is &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;closed&lt;/span&gt;, in a certain sense.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A wider range of patterns can be created if you add tiles like the ones below to your set.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEigF1KLmNCwe2I5pwFEfajoS8PXJID_b8ohx_0ynZy849Qv5BV5UDWDN3OOmcAG_l3PXXtZC0FmID_xYbDde7citWrxo-MD-EByOiLVxruX9b8a8rKRbL6BCa4TUZWW1qv6MRLYXxJBfnw/s1600-h/knots+B.jpg"&gt;&lt;img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5221432467406449858" style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center;" alt="" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEigF1KLmNCwe2I5pwFEfajoS8PXJID_b8ohx_0ynZy849Qv5BV5UDWDN3OOmcAG_l3PXXtZC0FmID_xYbDde7citWrxo-MD-EByOiLVxruX9b8a8rKRbL6BCa4TUZWW1qv6MRLYXxJBfnw/s320/knots+B.jpg" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Unfortunately, when you include these tiles, your set is no longer closed. An open question (at least as far as I know) is - how many more tiles would you need to add in order to create a closed set of tiles that includes these? Also, what would these tiles look like? Do they lead to "reasonable" looking knots?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The knot pattern below (better described as a woven set of three links) was made using tiles including the ones from the "extended" set above.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh15Uaka0D6rKDkbdqglVLnyh_aR1WK7OfXu4K8y7RYlXlcLP_VTQWeP97A6porT1fvGzWQ-_fCPl1EmtS2QGLra0tAY9bmRfpOBGNjcDC-UtMrbBiYe-Y4o_zZIU1-4qjadN5pZ0m6ehE/s1600-h/knots-B-collection.jpg"&gt;&lt;img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5221433352649027602" style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center;" alt="" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEh15Uaka0D6rKDkbdqglVLnyh_aR1WK7OfXu4K8y7RYlXlcLP_VTQWeP97A6porT1fvGzWQ-_fCPl1EmtS2QGLra0tAY9bmRfpOBGNjcDC-UtMrbBiYe-Y4o_zZIU1-4qjadN5pZ0m6ehE/s320/knots-B-collection.jpg" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content>
